05606nam a22008175i 9789814695626DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016si     fo  d z      eng d  a2016351181  a97898146956267 a10.1355/97898146956262doi  a(DE-B1597)491984  a(OCoLC)957701178  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aJZ5333.5.A84bT46 2016 7aSOC0530002bisacsh04a341.24732231 aC. Thompson, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDo Young People Know ASEAN? :bUpdate of a Ten-nation Survey /cEric C. Thompson, Chulanee Thianthai, Moe Thuzar. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF TABLES -- tAcknowledgements -- t1 Introduction -- t2 SUMMARY OF KEY FINDINGS -- t3 SUBJECTS AND METHODS -- t4 FINDINGS ON ATTITUDES, KNOWLEDGE, AND ORIENTATIONS TOWARD ASEAN -- t5 NATIONAL SUMMARIES -- t6 DESCRIPTIONS OF ASEAN AND MEMBER COUNTRIES -- t7 COGNITIVE MAPS OF ASEAN -- t8 CONCLUSIONS AND RECOMMENDATIONS -- tAppendix A: ASEAN SURVEY 2014 RESEARCHERS AND ASSISTANTS -- tAppendix B: ASEAN SURVEY 2014 survey questionnaire samples (list and map) -- tAppendix C: DEMOGRAPHICS OF RESPONDENTS -- tAppendix D: SALIENCE TABLES BASED ON LISTING ASEAN COUNTRIES -- tAppendix E: ATTITUDES TOWARD ASPECTS OF INTEGRATION AND COOPERATION -- tAppendix F: cognitive maps AND tables -- tAbout the authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2007, a survey – the first of its kind – was carried out to gauge young people’s awareness of and attitudes towards ASEAN, following the decision by ASEAN heads of state and government to accelerate the date for accomplishing an integrated ASEAN Community by 2015. Views and attitudes from university undergraduates in the ten ASEAN member states who participated in the survey indicated a nascent sense of identification as citizens of the region as well as their priorities for important aspects of regional integration. An update to the 2007 survey was carried out in 2014–15 among the same target population but with an expanded scope of twenty-two universities and institutes of higher learning across the ten member states. In the updated survey, we found that there are more ASEAN-positive attitudes region-wide, but there are also increases in ASEAN-ambivalent attitudes at country-level in some ASEAN members. Young people’s priorities for important aspects of regional integration have also shifted away from economic cooperation to tourism and development cooperation. New questions in the latest survey also allow us to demonstrate the descriptive vocabulary and cognitive maps students hold for the region and its nations. This book details the key findings of the updated survey compared to the earlier survey. These include nation-by-nation results and a summary of region-wide trends, as well as what they suggest for the prospects of ASEAN integration beyond 2015. These are assessed in a chapter providing broad recommendations for policymakers and educators in the ASEAN member states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInternational agencieszSoutheast Asia. 0aInternational agencies. 0aRegionalism (International organization) 0aRegionalism (International organization). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Regional Studies.2bisacsh1 aThianthai, Chulanee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aThuzar, Moe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066299308iTitle is part of eBook packa